1Ô∏è‚É£ What are Spring Annotations?
‚úÖ Definition

Spring Annotations are metadata used to configure Spring applications without XML.
They help Spring:
Create beans
Inject dependencies
Handle REST APIs

Manage configuration & lifecycle
üìå Introduced to reduce boilerplate and improve readability

üîπ 2Ô∏è‚É£ STEREOTYPE ANNOTATIONS (Bean Creation)
These annotations tell Spring which classes should become beans.
2.1 @Component
Definition
Marks a class as a Spring-managed bean

Key Points
Generic stereotype
Auto-detected during component scan
Parent of other stereotypes

2.2 @Service
Definition

Specialized @Component used for business logic layer.

@Service
public class PaymentService {
    public String pay() {
        return "Payment Successful";
    }
}

Output
Payment Successful

Why use @Service?
‚úî Better readability
‚úî Semantic meaning
‚úî AOP (transactions) applied easily

2.3 @Repository
Definition
Used for DAO / persistence layer.

@Repository
public class UserRepository {
    public String save() {
        return "User Saved";
    }
}

Output
User Saved
Special Feature

‚úî Converts DB exceptions to Spring DataAccessException

2.4 @Controller
Definition
Used for Spring MVC controllers (returns views).

@Controller
public class HomeController {

    @GetMapping("/home")
    public String home() {
        return "home";
    }
}

üìå Returns view name, not JSON.

2.5 @RestController
Definition
Combination of:

@Controller + @ResponseBody

@RestController
public class HelloController {

    @GetMapping("/hello")
    public String hello() {
        return "Hello Spring";
    }
}
Output
Hello Spring


‚úî Used for REST APIs
‚úî Returns JSON/String directly

üîπ 3Ô∏è‚É£ DEPENDENCY INJECTION ANNOTATIONS
3.1 @Autowired
Definition
Injects dependency automatically by type.

@Service
public class OrderService {

    @Autowired
    private PaymentService paymentService;

    public String placeOrder() {
        return paymentService.pay();
    }
}

Output
Payment Successful

Key Points
Can be used on field, setter, constructor
Constructor injection is best practice

3.2 Constructor Injection (Best Practice)
@Service
public class OrderService {

    private final PaymentService paymentService;

    public OrderService(PaymentService paymentService) {
        this.paymentService = paymentService;
    }
}

‚úî Immutable
‚úî Easy unit testing
‚úî Recommended by Spring team

3.3 @Qualifier
Definition
Used when multiple beans of same type exist.

@Service("upi")
class UpiPayment {}

@Service("card")
class CardPayment {}

@Autowired
@Qualifier("upi")
private PaymentService paymentService;

Key Point
Prevents NoUniqueBeanDefinitionException

3.4 @Primary
Definition
Marks default bean when multiple beans exist.

@Primary
@Service
class CardPayment {}

üîπ 4Ô∏è‚É£ CONFIGURATION ANNOTATIONS
4.1 @Configuration
Definition
Marks class as Spring configuration class.

@Configuration
public class AppConfig {
}

4.2 @Bean
Definition
Defines a bean explicitly.

@Configuration
public class AppConfig {

    @Bean
    public Employee employee() {
        return new Employee();
    }
}

Employee emp = context.getBean(Employee.class);

Output
Employee Bean Created

‚úî Used for third-party classes
‚úî Custom object creation

4.3 @ComponentScan
Definition
Tells Spring where to scan for beans.

@ComponentScan("com.app")

üîπ 5Ô∏è‚É£ PROPERTY & VALUE ANNOTATIONS
5.1 @Value
Definition
Injects values from application.properties.

app.name=SpringApp

@Value("${app.name}")
private String appName;

Output
SpringApp

5.2 @PropertySource
@PropertySource("classpath:custom.properties")

üîπ 6Ô∏è‚É£ BEAN SCOPE & LIFECYCLE ANNOTATIONS
6.1 @Scope
@Component
@Scope("prototype")
public class PrototypeBean {}

‚úî prototype
‚úî singleton
‚úî request
‚úî session

6.2 @Lazy
@Component
@Lazy
public class LazyBean {
    public LazyBean() {
        System.out.println("Lazy Bean Created");
    }
}

‚úî Created only when requested

6.3 @PostConstruct
@PostConstruct
public void init() {
    System.out.println("Bean Initialized");
}

6.4 @PreDestroy
@PreDestroy
public void destroy() {
    System.out.println("Bean Destroyed");
}

üìå Not called for prototype beans.

üîπ 7Ô∏è‚É£ WEB / REST ANNOTATIONS
7.1 Request Mapping Annotations
@GetMapping("/get")
@PostMapping("/post")
@PutMapping("/put")
@DeleteMapping("/delete")

7.2 @RequestParam
@GetMapping("/user")
public String user(@RequestParam String name) {
    return name;
}

7.3 @PathVariable
@GetMapping("/user/{id}")
public String user(@PathVariable int id) {
    return "ID: " + id;
}

7.4 @RequestBody
@PostMapping("/save")
public User save(@RequestBody User user) {
    return user;
}

üîπ 8Ô∏è‚É£ EXCEPTION HANDLING ANNOTATIONS
8.1 @ExceptionHandler
@ExceptionHandler(Exception.class)
public String handle() {
    return "Error occurred";
}

8.2 @RestControllerAdvice
Definition
Global exception handler.

@RestControllerAdvice
public class GlobalExceptionHandler {
}

‚úî Centralized
‚úî Clean code

üîπ 9Ô∏è‚É£ VALIDATION ANNOTATIONS
@NotNull
@Size(min=3, max=10)
@Email

@PostMapping("/save")
public void save(@Valid @RequestBody User user) {}

üî• MOST ASKED INTERVIEW & TRICKY QUESTIONS
